  "doc_id": "42790",
  "text": "Other assays for diagnosing CDI include commercially available enzyme immunoassays (EIA) [CITATION_1] . Despite the limitations associated with these tests [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , they are popular in laboratories because they are easy to use, relatively cheap, and have a short turnaround time. Some EIA are designed to detect GDH in feces, the ''common antigen'' on C. difficile strains, in addition to TcdA and TcdB, even though there are reports of reduced sensitivity for these tests [CITATION_4] . EIA that target GDH were initially said to have a higher sensitivity than those that only target TcdA or TcdB [CITATION_5] . Furthermore, some studies have suggested that EIA vary in their ability to detect certain RTs of C. difficile in human disease [CITATION_6] .",
